    <name>
      <text>43.2.1.1 Pearson r</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Hooke's law relates the extension of a spring under load to its extended length.</p><p>The following results were obtained experimentally.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<table style="height: 45px;" border="1" width="440">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="width: 66px; text-align: center;"><b>Load</b> (<strong>N</strong>)</td>
<td style="width: 66px; text-align: center;">\({@L1@}\)</td>
<td style="width: 67px; text-align: center;">\({@L2@}\)</td>
<td style="width: 67px; text-align: center;">\({@L3@}\)</td>
<td style="width: 67px; text-align: center;">\({@L4@}\)</td>
<td style="width: 67px; text-align: center;">\({@L5@}\)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 66px; text-align: center;"><b>Extension</b> (<strong>mm</strong>)</td>
<td style="width: 66px; text-align: center;">\({@E1@}\)</td>
<td style="width: 67px; text-align: center;">\({@E2@}\)</td>
<td style="width: 67px; text-align: center;">\({@E3@}\)</td>
<td style="width: 67px; text-align: center;">\({@E4@}\)</td>
<td style="width: 67px; text-align: center;">\({@E5@}\)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p></p>Calculate Pearson's \(r\) and the test statistic giving your answer to 3 decimal places. Test its significance at the \(5\%\) level. What conclusion can you draw?<p></p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li><p>\(r\) = [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p></li>

<li><p>\(r_{test}\) =[[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p></li>

<li><p>The critical value for a two-sided \(t\)-test at the \(5\%\) level read off from tables is [[input:ans3]]. Therefore&nbsp; we [[input:ans4]] reject the null hypothesis at the \(5\%\).<br></p><p></p><p>[[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]]<br></p><p>[[validation:ans4]][[feedback:prt4]]<br></p><p><br></p><p></p></li></ol>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Setting up a spreadsheet to do the calculations gives:</p><table border="1" width="534"><tbody><tr><td><b>Load</b> (\(x\))</td><td><b>Exten.</b> (\(y\))</td><td>\(xy\)</td><td>\(x^2\)</td><td>\(y^2\)</td></tr><tr><td>\({@L1@}\)</td><td>\({@E1@}\)</td><td>\({@L1*E1@}\)</td><td>\({@L1^2@}\)</td><td>\({@E1^2@}\)</td></tr><tr><td>\({@L2@}\)</td><td>\({@E2@}\)</td><td>\({@L2*E2@}\)</td><td>\({@L2^2@}\)</td><td>\({@E2^2@}\)</td></tr><tr><td>\({@L3@}\)</td><td>\({@E3@}\)</td><td>\({@L3*E3@}\)</td><td>\({@L3^2@}\)</td><td>\({@E3^2@}\)</td></tr><tr><td>\({@L4@}\)</td><td>\({@E4@}\)</td><td>\({@L4*E4@}\)</td><td>\({@L4^2@}\)</td><td>\({@E4^2@}\)</td></tr><tr><td>\({@L5@}\)</td><td>\({@E5@}\)</td><td>\({@L5*E5@}\)</td><td>\({@L5^2@}\)</td><td>\({@E5^2@}\)</td></tr><tr><td>\( \sum x = {@Sumx@} \)</td><td>\( \sum y = {@Sumy@} \)</td><td>\( \sum xy = {@Sumxy@} \)</td><td>\( \sum x^2 = {@Sumx2@} \)</td><td>\( \sum y^2 = {@Sumy2@} \)</td></tr></tbody></table>Substituting in the formula we developed for \(r\) gives the result&nbsp;<p>&nbsp;\[ r = \dfrac{n \sum xy - \sum x \sum y }{\sqrt{\left( n \sum x^2 - \left( \sum x \right) ^2 \right)} \left( n \sum y^2 - \left( \sum y \right)^2 \right) } \]</p><p>&nbsp;\[ = \dfrac{ {@n@} \times {@Sumxy@} - {@Sumx@} \times {@Sumy@} }{ \sqrt{ \left( {@n@} \times {@Sumx2@} - \left( {@Sumx@} \right) ^2 \right) \left( {@n@} \times {@Sumy2@} - \left( {@Sumy@} \right)^2 \right) }} = {@ta1@} \]</p><p>and then</p><p>\[r_{test} = \dfrac{r\sqrt{n-2}}{\sqrt{1 - r^2}} = {@ta2@}\]</p>Hence, since the critical value for a two-sided \(t\)-test at the \(5\%\) level read off from tables is \(3.182\) we see that since \( {@ta2@} &gt; 3.182 \) we <b>can</b> <span><span style="">reject</span> </span>the null hypothesis at the \(5\%\) level and conclude that the correlation coefficient is significantly different from zero.<br><p></p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
